<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-12T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-12T19:00:00-05:00" n="742" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d742">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11047: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul General at Shanghai</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-12T19:00:00-05:00">November 12, 1937—7
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>544. Reference Commander-in-Chief’s 0012—1930 [<hi rend="italic">1826</hi>].<note n="14" xml:id="d742fn14"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_516"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 516</ref>; see also Admiral
                                    Yarnell’s telegram of November 9, 7:10 p.m., <ref target="#pg_671">p. 671</ref>.</note> With regard to
                                Japanese use of Soochow Creek, Department is of the opinion that
                                action, if any, in opposition thereto should be confined solely to
                                appropriate representations. Inform Commander-in-Chief.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>